<dl id="s18016cd"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us18" href="#s18016cd">Penelope: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s18all.htm#s18016cd">sector 16(cd)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Squad of buglers / parading / answers</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">There is nothing that stirs me quite so much as the bugle. Twice a day it startles us with its piercing blast, as it follows instantly the gun-fire at sunrise and sunset. But this does not thrill me as when I hear it blown on some far-off height, and dying away in a valley below, or <mark>answered</mark> back from a yet more distant point, like a mountain echo. One morning I was taking a walk to Europa Point, and as the path leads upward I came upon several <mark>squads of buglers</mark> (I counted a dozen men in one of them) practising their &ldquo;calls&rdquo; <small> Henry M. Field, <a name="HMFG" href="/udra/udex.htm#hmfg"><cite title="source">Gibralter</cite></a> (1888), p 31</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
